    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">

Response to MORMAN and FROST:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="17" relname="span">

I agree that _Telling the Truth..._ is a good ideological resource for STS
fending off the attacks of scientists,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="16" relname="span"> since it shows how many of the
constructivist critiques of science (and its history) make sense,</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="concession"> even
within an Enlightenment framework of &apos;the truth will set you free.&apos;</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="21" relname="span">

However, matters aren&apos;t so cut-and-dry</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="20" relname="span"> because Appleby, Hunt &amp; Jacob (AHJ)
don&apos;t see themselves as mere ideological resources.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="18" relname="span"> They actually believe
in the Enlightenment project,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> and, between the lines, you can see that
they&apos;re none too pleased about the cultural consequences of an unrepentant
relativism.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="19" relname="span"> In fact, their positive thesis is that a strong commitment to
freedom of inquiry -- which for them, like JS Mill, is the cornerstone of
democracy -- requires that the consequences of inquiry be taken seriously,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration">
i.e. you can be shown wrong or right by some &apos;truth&apos; (however corrigible)
that someone uncovers.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="23" relname="span"> They argue that the more radical
postmodernist/relativist forms of inquiry undermines this requirement by
denying that any claim ever decisively bears on any other claim.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="elaboration"> By the
end of the book, it becomes clear that they see this devaluation of the
consequences of inquiry to be just as bad as placing political
restrictions on inquiry. </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="22" relname="evidence">

An indicator of AHJ&apos;s sensibilities is their endorsement of the &apos;Hard 
Program&apos; that Segerstrale, Schmaus, and Jesseph pubished in _Social 
Epistemology_ a couple of years ago -- the key to which is that you need 
to account for the scientist&apos;s own understanding of her pursuit in order 
to have an adequate understanding of science.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="26" relname="span">

My guess is that FROST&apos;s synthesis of AHJ and the radical core of science 
studies is not going to be very easy</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="14" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> because it would first require that 
the people on &apos;our&apos; side take more seriously the political consequences of 
their epistemological commitments.</segment>
